<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>What to Look For in a Good Kit</h2>

  <h3>1. Standard Tray Sizes</h3>
  <p>
    Kits that use standard sizes are easier to expand and replace parts for later.
  </p>

  <h3>2. Sturdy Bottom Tray</h3>
  <p>
    A strong base makes watering easier and prevents bending or leaks.
  </p>

  <h3>3. Useful Cell Size</h3>
  <p>
    Cells should provide enough room for early growth without crowding too quickly.
  </p>

  <h3>4. Optional, Not Mandatory Extras</h3>
  <p>
    Domes can help with germination, but lighting and airflow are usually more important long-term.
  </p>

  <h3>5. Expandability</h3>
  <p>
    A good kit should not lock you into one fixed system.
  </p>
</section>

